<ol class="blogroll wp-dark-mode-bg-image">
<li class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><span class="heap-of-link_name wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><a id="link-54863" class="track_this_link wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/2025/melvyn-bragg-decides-to-step-down-from-presenting-in-our-time/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Since 1998, the BBC show “In Our Time” has aired over 150 episodes on philosophy</a></span> <span class="heap-of-link_description wp-dark-mode-bg-image">&#8212; its creator and longtime host, Melvyn Bragg, is retiring. </span><span class="heap-of-link_name wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><a id="link-54864" class="track_this_link wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01f0vzr?page=1" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Check out the show&#8217;s Philosophy Episodes</a></span></li>
<li class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><span class="heap-of-link_name wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><a id="link-54861" class="track_this_link wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://richardpettigrew.substack.com/p/access-to-universities-and-the-distributive" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">On the current model, “all of your undergraduate education is taken in one intensive, all-consuming dose, usually at the end of your teenage years”</a></span> <span class="heap-of-link_description wp-dark-mode-bg-image">&#8212; &#8220;This was always a bizarre idea, I think, but it is becoming stranger and stranger.&#8221; Richard Pettigrew on the structure of higher education</span></li>
<li class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><span class="heap-of-link_name wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><a id="link-54847" class="track_this_link wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://sootyempiric.blogspot.com/2025/09/on-tension-between-liberalism-and.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">“Liberalism and animal rights sit uneasily together”</a></span> <span class="heap-of-link_description wp-dark-mode-bg-image">&#8212; Jonathan Birch explains why, and explores, with the help of J.M. Coetzee, ways of resolving the tension</span></li>
<li class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><span class="heap-of-link_name wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><a id="link-54836" class="track_this_link wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/technology/as-ceos-predict-ai-will-rival-humans-in-5-years-shark-tank-s-daniel-lubetzky-tells-gen-z-to-get-off-tiktok-and-study-greek-philosophers-to-get-ahead/ar-AA1LthhQ" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">“Being a critical thinker is in high demand, and [there’s] going to become greater demand”</a></span> <span class="heap-of-link_description wp-dark-mode-bg-image">&#8212; billionaire businessman (and Shark Tank judge) Daniel Lubetzky thinks that in a world with AI, studying philosophy is valuable</span></li>
<li class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><span class="heap-of-link_name wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><a id="link-54845" class="track_this_link wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://certifiedaifreeskillsandknowledge.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">“Certified AI-Free Skills and Knowledge”: a place to list courses in which “all student work is done in person, offline, and on paper”</a></span> <span class="heap-of-link_description wp-dark-mode-bg-image">&#8212; created by Marc Champagne</span></li>
<li class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><span class="heap-of-link_name wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><a id="link-54833" class="track_this_link wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/platos-cave-and-the-stubborn-persistence-of-ignorance/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">“We… are haunted by things we do not know we do not know; and we cannot imagine how drastically those unknowns would alter our lives and our view of the world”</a></span> <span class="heap-of-link_description wp-dark-mode-bg-image">&#8212; Daniel R. DeNicola on understanding ignorance</span></li>
<li class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><span class="heap-of-link_name wp-dark-mode-bg-image"><a id="link-54813" class="track_this_link wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://www.csmonitor.com/Books/Book-Reviews/2025/0715/the-greatest-possible-good-novel-ben-brooks" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">“Arthur, [now] a changed man… approaches everyone he meets with the shallow pond problem”</a></span> <span class="heap-of-link_description wp-dark-mode-bg-image">&#8212; The Greatest Possible Good, by Ben Brooks, is a novel in which one of the characters, inspired by Peter Singer, becomes an effective altruist</span></li>
</ol>
<p>Mini-Heap posts usually appear when several new items accumulate in the <a class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://dailynous.com/heap-of-links/">Heap of Links</a>, a collection of items from around the web that may be of interest to philosophers. The Heap of Links consists partly of suggestions from readers; if you find something online that you think would be of interest to the philosophical community, please <a class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="mailto:dailynouseditor@gmail.com">send it in</a> for consideration for the Heap. Thank you.<br class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image" /><a class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://dailynous.com/2025/08/29/mini-heap-674/">Previous edition</a>.</p><p>The post <a href="https://dailynous.com/2025/09/03/mini-heap-675/">Mini-Heap</a> first appeared on <a href="https://dailynous.com">Daily Nous</a>.</p>